---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Home" description="A personal archive tool for Famly-using households. Pulls your kid's photos and videos from the nursery feed onto your own disk with full EXIF and XMP metadata.">
  <p class="page-eyebrow">photo archive · cli</p>
  <h1 class="page-title">bairn</h1>
  <p class="page-lede">
    A personal archive for Famly-using households. <code>bairn</code>
    pulls your kid's photos and videos from the nursery feed onto your
    own disk, with the post body, the educator's name, and the date
    embedded into each file via EXIF and XMP. Your child's photo
    history does not depend on Famly continuing to exist as a company.
  </p>

  <section class="section">
    <h2>What it does</h2>
    <ul class="what-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Pull</strong>
        Reads your Famly nursery feed and downloads every photo and
        video it has access to, into date-organized folders on disk.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Embed</strong>
        Writes the caption, the educator's name, the date, and the kid
        tags into the file's own EXIF and XMP metadata — readable by
        any photo viewer or archival workflow, today and in twenty
        years.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Resume</strong>
        Re-running is safe. Already-downloaded items are skipped; only
        new posts since the last run are fetched.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Survive the vendor</strong>
        Once a file is on disk with metadata embedded, Famly going
        away, your account closing, or the API breaking does not lose
        the history. The on-disk copy is the source of truth.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <h2>Install</h2>
    <p>Single Go binary. Latest release lives on GitLab:</p>
    <pre>go install gitlab.com/dunn.dev/bairn/cmd/bairn@latest</pre>
    <p>
      Or grab a prebuilt binary from
      <a href="https://gitlab.com/dunn.dev/bairn/-/releases">the releases page</a>
      (linux/amd64, linux/arm64, darwin/arm64).
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <h2>Who this is for</h2>
    <p>
      A parent, co-parent, or household admin whose kid's daycare uses
      Famly and who wants a permanent local copy of every photo and
      video the educators post, with metadata that survives any future
      tooling change. If your school doesn't use Famly, or if you're
      happy enough with how the mobile app surfaces history,
      <code>bairn</code> is not for you.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <h2>What it isn't</h2>
    <p>
      Not a privacy gateway. Every piece of context the vendor exposes
      lands inside the file you keep — that's the whole point of EXIF
      and XMP for archival. What happens to those files after you have
      them is your call. Not a multi-tenant service either: one
      binary, one household, one disk.
    </p>
  </section>
</Layout>
